32
00:04:11.120 --> 00:04:19.500
The first of these technologies is Color Prime. With Color Prime, 
thicker color filters are used to reproduce more colors in the spectrum. 

33
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:28.900
Conventional LED TVs use a basic color filter that typically reproduces about 97%
of the colors in the HDTV color space. 

34
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:38.550
However, with Color Prime technology, LG Super UHD TVs can expand that color by up to 125% of HDTV color space. 

35
00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:48.900
That’s 28% percent more color available that can be viewed on Super UHD TVs! 
More colors mean more “true-to-life” images viewed on Super UHD TVs.

36
00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:57.950
The second of the broad color technologies that build even further upon 
Color Prime is Billion Rich Color technology. 

37
00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:12.000
Conventional LED TVs can only display combinations of 256 shades each of red, green, and blue, 
which can create about 16.8 million colors. Sound like a lot? Maybe, but it actually isn’t. 

38
00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:19.450
The human eye can see much more. As a result, picture irregularities such as 
contrast bandwidth and color banding can result.

39
00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:33.120
With LG Super UHD TVs, each red, blue, and green subpixel can display 1,024 shades, 
which creates over one Billion Colors! Now we’re talking.

40
00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:45.800
How does this alleviate contrast bandwidth limitations? 
Imagine you have a dark scene with bright elements, such a river illuminated by moonlight. 

41
00:05:46.300 --> 00:05:57.000
The TV will only accurately display shadow detail in the dark parts while washing out the bright parts, 
or only accurately displays the bright parts while muddying dark areas of the screen. 

42
00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:03.800
With over one Billion Rich Colors, the content can have more detail in the bright areas 
AND the dark areas of the image. 

43
00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:08.000
Color banding is also alleviated with over one Billion Rich Colors.

44
00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:19.600
The fact that conventional TVs can only display 256 shades of each subpixel causes problems when 
there are multiple shades of the same color that go from dark to light or vice versa. 

45
00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:28.000
Imagine a sky with a hot air balloon. The sky isn’t all one uniform shade, and since 
conventional sets have a limited number of colors to choose from, 

46
00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:33.000
the cutoff between shades is sharp, leaving the customer viewing obvious bands in-between. 

47
00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:42.400
With technologies to display over one Billion Rich Colors, the transition is smooth between shades and
exhibits a scene more like you’d see in real life. 

